What are property taxes?

Property tax is owed by property owners annually, for both residential and commercial properties.

These liabilities are decided per Property Parcel, and each parcel is uniquely identifiable with a 14-digit Property Index Number or PIN.

Every PIN belongs to multiple tax districts (local government bodies), that each require funding for purposes like operating schools, libraries, parks etc.

The Cook County Assessorâs Office, the State, and county taxing districts (schools, parks, etc.) work together to calculate fair property taxes for residents.

Each year you receive one tax bill that is split across two payments. The first installment is due by March 1st and will be 55% of last yearâs tax bill. The second installment is sent around June 30 and is for the remaining taxes due.

Why Did my Property Tax Bill Change?

The tax bill for Parcel (17-22-107-089-0000) was approximately $3,431 in 2021 and $4,139 in 2023, resulting in an increase of $708. This change can be broken down into two main components as shown below. The largest change in your bill was due to your propertyâs share of all residential properties changing.

Your tax bill increased by approximately $375 due to your propertyâs assessed value going up faster than other properties in your area on average.

Your tax bill increased by approximately $298 due to the increase in your taxing districtsâ levies. This is the change in the tax bill outside your control, is the same for everyone, and refers to the increase in the cost of providing services.

There is also a $35 increase that was caused by a combination of both factors.

Your tax levy increased and your assessed value increased, while your combined tax bill increased.

Property tax bills are calculated based on the Tax Levy and the value of your property. First, the government determines the Tax Levy, or total amount of taxes imposed by the government. This levy is then divided among all property owners in the area. Your share of this levy depends on how much your property is worth compared to the total value of all properties.

Your final tax bill reflects your propertyâs share of the total taxable value in the area, meaning you contribute to the Tax Levy in proportion to your propertyâs worth.

How did your propertyâs change in price affect my bill?

This share is how much your propertyâs taxable value, or its Equalized Assessed Value, makes up of the the taxable value of all properties, called the Tax Base. The Tax Base is the combination of the taxable value of all residential and commercial properties.

This share can be broken up into two parts that impact your bill:

(A) Change from Exemptions
(B) Change from your Propertyâs Share of all Residential Properties
(C) Change from Commercial-Residential Ratio

Appendix A: Calculating Equalized Assessed Value

First, start with the Fair Market Value and multiply by the Level of Assessment, which is 10% for all residential property, and the State Equalizer, a multiplier whose goal is to make property tax rates roughly equal across all IL counties. Both of these values are the same for all property owners in this area. After this, subtract your valid exemptions. 1

The resulting value is the Equalized Assessed Value. \[\$196K \times 10.00\% \times 3.0163 = \$58,981\] \[\$58,981 - \$0 = \$58,981\]

Appendix B: Calculating a Single Districtâs Tax Bill

Your property is in many tax districts.

Now, letâs look at the line item of the bill for Parcel (17-22-107-089-0000) in 2023 for Board Of Education -

Tax District Agency Tax Base Agency Tax Levy Agency Tax Rate Final Tax Owed
School Board Of Education $99.65B $3.82B 3.83% $2,258.38

For the purpose of operating Board Of Education, in 2023, it needs to collect $4b in order to provide services.

Tax District Agency Tax Base Agency Tax Levy Agency Tax Rate Final Tax Owed
School Board Of Education $99.65B $3.82B 3.83% $2,258.38

But where can Board Of Education raise the money from? From all the properties within the district boundaries!
The total taxable value of all properties falling in Board Of Education make up its tax base. For 2023, this was $100b

Tax District Agency Tax Base Agency Tax Levy Agency Tax Rate Final Tax Owed
School Board Of Education $99.65B $3.82B 3.83% $2,258.38

The cost of services of Board Of Education is therefore divided amongst all the property owners, and Board Of Education sets its agency tax rate equal to:

\[ \mathrm{{Levy \over Base} = Tax \hspace{0.1cm} rate} \]

Using real numbers, the tax rate equals: \[ \mathrm{\$4B \over \$100B} = 3.83\% \]

Tax District Agency Tax Base Agency Tax Levy Agency Tax Rate Final Tax Owed
School Board Of Education $99.65B $3.82B 3.83% $2,258.38

How much do you owe Board Of Education?

As the owner of Parcel (17-22-107-089-0000), in the year 2023 your property is worth $196k, of that, your taxable amount (or addition to the tax base) is $58,981.

The previously calculated Rate is then applied to your Addition To The Tax Base:

\[ (\$58,981 * 3.83\%) = \$2,258 \]

This is the part of your bill that goes to to the Board Of Education
